tter's hunger and impetuousness to persuade him to part with his birthright ‘for a mess of potage’. The name is traditionally interpreted as coming from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’: Jacob is said to have been born holding on to Esau's heel. In English usage the name <i>Jacob</i> is regarded as distinct from the name   James  , but they are of identical origin. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Yaqub  ,   Yakub  ,   Yacoub  , or   Yacob  , Slovenian   Jakob   and <b>Jakop</b>, Czech and Slovak   Jakub  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Jacobs   and   Jacobson  ). The name <i>Jacob</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Chacko  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"Gente","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant spelling of   Gente   or a habitational name from Gentha in Saxony Anhalt, east of Wittenberg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mabila","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Latin: Contraction of Amabel, like a lily fair."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mabila della Gente was born before 1255, in Italy as the daughter of Giberto Gente. She married Guido da Correggio. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Bef 1255–":"enne 1255–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1225–1299":"1225–1299","1270–1326":"1270–1326","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1326":"1326","1225":"1225","Bef 1255":"enne 1255","1299":"1299","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","1270":"1270","Castellero, Asti, Piemonte, Itália":"Castellero, Asti, Piemonte, Itaalia","Italy":"Itaalia"},"fi":{"Bef 1255–":"ennen vuotta 1255–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1225–1299":"1225–1299","1270–1326":"127